{"title_page": "Neil Malhotra", "text_new": "{{short description|American political scientist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Neil Malhotra\n| image             =\n| image_upright     = \n| alt               = \n| caption           =\n| birth_date        = \n| birth_place       = \n| death_date        = \n| death_place       =\n| nationality       = [[United States|American]]\n| fields            = {{ubl|[[Political science]]}}\n| alma_mater        = {{ubl|[[Yale University]]|[[Stanford University]]}}\n| workplaces        = {{ubl|[[Stanford University]]|[[University of Pennsylvania]]}}\n| doctoral_advisor  = \n| doctoral_students = \n| known_for         = \n| awards            = {{ubl|Top 40 Under 40, ''Poets & Quants''|Emerging Scholar Award, [[American Political Science Association|APSA]] Elections}}\n}}\n'''Neil Malhotra''' is an [[United States|American]] political economist. He is the Edith M. Cornell Professor of Political Economy in the Graduate School of Business at [[Stanford University]], where he is also the Louise and Claude N. Rosenbrg, Jr. Director of the Center for Social Innovation. He studies the [[politics of the United States]], [[survey methodology]], and voter behavior in elections, including work on retrospective voting and on the politics of disaster preparedness and relief.\n\n==Education and early work==\nMalhotra attended [[Yale University]], where he earned his BA in economics in 2002.<ref name=profile>{{cite web |url=https://www.gsb.stanford.edu/faculty-research/faculty/neil-malhotra |title=Neil Malhotra |publisher=Stanford University |year=2014 |access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref> At Yale he was mentored by [[Donald Green]], whom he has credited with inspiring him to become a political scientist.<ref name=top40>{{cite news |url=https://poetsandquants.com/2015/04/16/2015-best-40-under-40-professors-neil-malhotra-stanford-gsb/?pq-category=business-school-news |title=2015 Best 40 Under 40 Professors: Neil Malhotra, Stanford GSB |work=Poets & Quants |date=16 April 2015 |last=Carter |first=Andrea |access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref> He then attended Stanford University, earning an MA in 2005 and a PhD in 2008.<ref name=profile/>\n\nAfter obtaining his PhD, Malhotra joined the faculty at the Stanford University Graduate School of Business.<ref name=profile/> He remained there until 2010, when he moved to the political science department at the [[University of Pennsylvania]].<ref name=profile/> In 2011, he returned to the Graduate School of Business at Stanford University, where he is also affiliated with the political science department.<ref name=profile/>\n\n==Career==\n===Academic positions===\nSince 2015, Malhotra has been the Louise and Claude N. Rosenberg Jr. Director of the Center for Social Innovation. In 2017 he was named the Edith M. Cornell Professor of Political Economy,<ref name=profile/> and in 2019 he was named the The Susan Ford Dorsey Faculty Fellow at the Stanford University Graduate School of Business.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://professorships.stanford.edu/content/Graduate%20School%20of%20Business?page=1 |title=Graduate School of Business professorships |publisher=Stanford University Graduate School of Business |year=2020 |access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Research===\nMalhotra has published work on American politics, voting behavior in elections and other forms of political behavior, and the methodology of survey research.<ref name=profile/> His work on voter behavior includes research on the problem of retrospective voting, and how strongly voters consider past events when arriving at a vote choice.<ref name=rsf/> Malhotra has also published work on disaster response by governments, and how that response is rewarded or punished by voters. In 2009 he published the study \"Myopic voters and natural disaster policy\" in the ''[[American Political Science Review]]'',<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Andrew Healy |author2=Neil Malhotra |title=Myopic Voters and Natural Disaster Policy |journal=American Political Science Review |volume=103 |issue=3 |year=2009 |pages=387\u2013406}}</ref> which led to consultations with the [[Federal Emergency Management Agency]] about optimal disaster preparedness.<ref name=top40/> The study showed evidence that voters reward incumbents for disaster relief spending, but not for disaster preparedness spending.<ref name=top40/><ref name=atlantic/><ref>{{cite journal |author1=Andrew Healy |author2=Neil Malhotra |title=Myopic Voters and Natural Disaster Policy |journal=American Political Science Review |volume=103 |issue=3 |date=August 2009 |pages=387\u2013406 |doi=doi.org/10.1017/S0003055409990104}}</ref>\n\nSince 2018, Malhotra has been a frequent contributor to ''[[Forbes]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/neilmalhotra/#2354d22615d1 |title=Neil Malotra Contributor |publisher=Forbes |year=2020 |access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref> He has been quoted or cited in ''[[The Washington Post]]'' regarding topics such as government crisis response strategies,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2020/03/14/house-moved-quickly-covid-19-response-bill-these-4-takeaways-explain-whats-likely-happen-next/ |title=The House moved quickly on a covid-19 response bill. These 4 takeaways explain what\u2019s likely to happen next |date=14 March 2020 |work=The Washington Post |last=Binder |first=Sarah |access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref> the effects of major external events on elections,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/monkey-cage/wp/2014/07/09/could-brazils-world-cup-loss-really-affect-the-coming-presidential-election/ |title=Could Brazil's World Cup loss really affect the coming presidential election? |date=9 July 2014 |work=The Washington Post |last=Tucker |first=Joshua |access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref> and [[Corporate social responsibility|corporate responsibility]],<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/2019/08/21/what-watch-now-that-ceos-have-rewritten-purpose-corporation/ |title=What to watch for now that CEOs have rewritten the purpose of the corporation |date=21 August 2019 |work=The Washington Post |last=McGregor |first=Jena |access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref> and on similar topics in venues like ''[[The Atlantic]]'',<ref name=atlantic>{{cite news |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2020/04/most-important-number-trumps-re-election-chances/609376/ |title=The Economy Is Collapsing. So Are Trump's Reelection Chances |date=3 April 2020 |work=The Atlantic |last=Lowrey |first=Annie |access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'',<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/30/upshot/bernie-sanders-indian-food.html |title=Bernie Sanders, and How Indian Food Can Predict Vote Choice |date=30 January 2020 |work=The New York Times |last=Vavreck |first=Lynn |access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/18/opinion/trump-fundraising-donors.html |title=The Changing Shape of the Parties Is Changing Where They Get Their Money |date=18 September 2019 |work=The New York Times |last=Edsall |first=Thomas B. |access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref> and ''[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]''.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://fortune.com/2019/11/22/stacey-abrams-carries-the-fight-against-voter-suppression/ |title=Stacey Abrams Carries the Fight Against Voter Suppression |date=22 November 2019 |work=Fortune |last=McGirt |first=Ellen |access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Awards===\nDuring 2012\u20132013, Malhotra was the recipient of a grant from the [[Russell Sage Foundation]] to study how voters weight recent events compared to events in the distant past, which is related to the question of retrospective voting in American politics.<ref name=rsf>{{cite web |url=https://www.russellsage.org/visiting-scholars/neil-malhotra |title=Neil Malhotra |publisher=Russell Sage Foundation |year=2013 |access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, ''Poets & Quants'' listed Malhotra as one of the top 40 professors under 40 years old.<ref name=top40/> In 2016, Malhotra won the Emerging Scholar Award from the Elections, Public Opinion, and Voting Behavior Section of the [[American Political Science Association]], which \"is awarded to the top scholar in the field who is within 10 years of her or his PhD\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/ps-political-science-and-politics/article/2016-apsa-organized-section-awards-presented/4E5823EDFAFC468C6061BC839C8D08D6/core-reader |title=Emerging Scholar Award |publisher=American Political Science Association |year=2016 |access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Selected works==\n*\"Completion Time and Response Order Effects in Web Surveys\", ''Public Opinion Quarterly'' 72(5):914\u2013934 (2008)\n*\"Myopic Voters and Natural Disaster Policy\", with Andrew Healy, ''American Political Science Review'' 103(3):387\u2013406 (2009)\n*\"Irrelevant events affect voters' evaluations of government performance\", with Andrew J. Healy and Cecilia Hyunjung Mo, ''PNAS'' 107(29):12804\u201312809 (2010)\n*\"Retrospective Voting Reconsidered\", with Andrew Healy, ''Annual Review of Political Science'' 16:285\u2013306 (2013)\n*\"Publication bias in the social sciences: Unlocking the file drawer\", with Annie Franco and Gabor Simonovits, ''Science'' 345(6203):1502\u20131505 (2014)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Malhotra, Neil}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American political scientists]]\n[[Category:Yale University alumni]]\n[[Category:Stanford University alumni]]\n[[Category:Stanford University faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Pennsylvania faculty]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American political scientist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Neil Malhotra\n| image             =\n| image_upright     = \n| alt               = \n| caption           =\n| birth_date        = \n| birth_place       = \n| death_date        = \n| death_place       =\n| nationality       = [[United States|American]]\n| fields            = {{ubl|[[Political science]]}}\n| alma_mater        = {{ubl|[[Yale University]]|[[Stanford University]]}}\n| workplaces        = {{ubl|[[Stanford University]]|[[University of Pennsylvania]]}}\n| doctoral_advisor  = \n| doctoral_students = \n| known_for         = \n| awards            = {{ubl|Top 40 Under 40, ''Poets & Quants''|Emerging Scholar Award, [[American Political Science Association|APSA]] Elections}}\n}}\n'''Neil Malhotra''' is an [[United States|American]] political economist. He is the Edith M. Cornell Professor of Political Economy in the Graduate School of Business at [[Stanford University]], where he is also the Louise and Claude N. Rosenbrg, Jr. Director of the Center for Social Innovation. He studies the [[politics of the United States]], [[survey methodology]], and voter behavior in elections, including work on retrospective voting and on the politics of disaster preparedness and relief.\n\n==Education and early work==\nMalhotra attended [[Yale University]], where he earned his BA in economics in 2002.<ref name=profile>{{cite web |url=https://www.gsb.stanford.edu/faculty-research/faculty/neil-malhotra |title=Neil Malhotra |publisher=Stanford University |year=2014 |access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref> At Yale he was mentored by [[Donald Green]], whom he has credited with inspiring him to become a political scientist.<ref name=top40>{{cite news |url=https://poetsandquants.com/2015/04/16/2015-best-40-under-40-professors-neil-malhotra-stanford-gsb/?pq-category=business-school-news |title=2015 Best 40 Under 40 Professors: Neil Malhotra, Stanford GSB |work=Poets & Quants |date=16 April 2015 |last=Carter |first=Andrea |access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref> He then attended Stanford University, earning an MA in 2005 and a PhD in 2008.<ref name=profile/>\n\nAfter obtaining his PhD, Malhotra joined the faculty at the Stanford University Graduate School of Business.<ref name=profile/> He remained there until 2010, when he moved to the political science department at the [[University of Pennsylvania]].<ref name=profile/> In 2011, he returned to the Graduate School of Business at Stanford University, where he is also affiliated with the political science department.<ref name=profile/>\n\n==Career==\n===Academic positions===\nSince 2015, Malhotra has been the Louise and Claude N. Rosenberg Jr. Director of the Center for Social Innovation. In 2017 he was named the Edith M. Cornell Professor of Political Economy,<ref name=profile/> and in 2019 he was named the The Susan Ford Dorsey Faculty Fellow at the Stanford University Graduate School of Business.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://professorships.stanford.edu/content/Graduate%20School%20of%20Business?page=1 |title=Graduate School of Business professorships |publisher=Stanford University Graduate School of Business |year=2020 |access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Research===\nMalhotra has published work on American politics, voting behavior in elections and other forms of political behavior, and the methodology of survey research.<ref name=profile/> His work on voter behavior includes research on the problem of retrospective voting, and how strongly voters consider past events when arriving at a vote choice.<ref name=rsf/> Malhotra has also published work on disaster response by governments, and how that response is rewarded or punished by voters. In 2009 he published the study \"Myopic voters and natural disaster policy\" in the ''[[American Political Science Review]]'',<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Andrew Healy |author2=Neil Malhotra |title=Myopic Voters and Natural Disaster Policy |journal=American Political Science Review |volume=103 |issue=3 |year=2009 |pages=387\u2013406}}</ref> which led to consultations with the [[Federal Emergency Management Agency]] about optimal disaster preparedness.<ref name=top40/> The study showed evidence that voters reward incumbents for disaster relief spending, but not for disaster preparedness spending.<ref name=atlantic/><ref name=top40/><ref>{{cite journal |author1=Andrew Healy |author2=Neil Malhotra |title=Myopic Voters and Natural Disaster Policy |journal=American Political Science Review |volume=103 |issue=3 |date=August 2009 |pages=387\u2013406 |doi=doi.org/10.1017/S0003055409990104}}</ref>\n\nSince 2018, Malhotra has been a frequent contributor to ''[[Forbes]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/neilmalhotra/#2354d22615d1 |title=Neil Malotra Contributor |publisher=Forbes |year=2020 |access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref> He has been quoted or cited in ''[[The Washington Post]]'' regarding topics such as government crisis response strategies,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2020/03/14/house-moved-quickly-covid-19-response-bill-these-4-takeaways-explain-whats-likely-happen-next/ |title=The House moved quickly on a covid-19 response bill. These 4 takeaways explain what\u2019s likely to happen next |date=14 March 2020 |work=The Washington Post |last=Binder |first=Sarah |access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref> the effects of major external events on elections,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/monkey-cage/wp/2014/07/09/could-brazils-world-cup-loss-really-affect-the-coming-presidential-election/ |title=Could Brazil's World Cup loss really affect the coming presidential election? |date=9 July 2014 |work=The Washington Post |last=Tucker |first=Joshua |access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref> and [[Corporate social responsibility|corporate responsibility]],<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/2019/08/21/what-watch-now-that-ceos-have-rewritten-purpose-corporation/ |title=What to watch for now that CEOs have rewritten the purpose of the corporation |date=21 August 2019 |work=The Washington Post |last=McGregor |first=Jena |access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref> and on similar topics in venues like ''[[The Atlantic]]'',<ref name=atlantic>{{cite news |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2020/04/most-important-number-trumps-re-election-chances/609376/ |title=The Economy Is Collapsing. So Are Trump's Reelection Chances |date=3 April 2020 |work=The Atlantic |last=Lowrey |first=Annie |access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'',<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/30/upshot/bernie-sanders-indian-food.html |title=Bernie Sanders, and How Indian Food Can Predict Vote Choice |date=30 January 2020 |work=The New York Times |last=Vavreck |first=Lynn |access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/18/opinion/trump-fundraising-donors.html |title=The Changing Shape of the Parties Is Changing Where They Get Their Money |date=18 September 2019 |work=The New York Times |last=Edsall |first=Thomas B. |access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref> and ''[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]''.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://fortune.com/2019/11/22/stacey-abrams-carries-the-fight-against-voter-suppression/ |title=Stacey Abrams Carries the Fight Against Voter Suppression |date=22 November 2019 |work=Fortune |last=McGirt |first=Ellen |access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Awards===\nDuring 2012\u20132013, Malhotra was the recipient of a grant from the [[Russell Sage Foundation]] to study how voters weight recent events compared to events in the distant past, which is related to the question of retrospective voting in American politics.<ref name=rsf>{{cite web |url=https://www.russellsage.org/visiting-scholars/neil-malhotra |title=Neil Malhotra |publisher=Russell Sage Foundation |year=2013 |access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, ''Poets & Quants'' listed Malhotra as one of the top 40 professors under 40 years old.<ref name=top40/> In 2016, Malhotra won the Emerging Scholar Award from the Elections, Public Opinion, and Voting Behavior Section of the [[American Political Science Association]], which \"is awarded to the top scholar in the field who is within 10 years of her or his PhD\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/ps-political-science-and-politics/article/2016-apsa-organized-section-awards-presented/4E5823EDFAFC468C6061BC839C8D08D6/core-reader |title=Emerging Scholar Award |publisher=American Political Science Association |year=2016 |access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Selected works==\n*\"Completion Time and Response Order Effects in Web Surveys\", ''Public Opinion Quarterly'' 72(5):914\u2013934 (2008)\n*\"Myopic Voters and Natural Disaster Policy\", with Andrew Healy, ''American Political Science Review'' 103(3):387\u2013406 (2009)\n*\"Irrelevant events affect voters' evaluations of government performance\", with Andrew J. Healy and Cecilia Hyunjung Mo, ''PNAS'' 107(29):12804\u201312809 (2010)\n*\"Retrospective Voting Reconsidered\", with Andrew Healy, ''Annual Review of Political Science'' 16:285\u2013306 (2013)\n*\"Publication bias in the social sciences: Unlocking the file drawer\", with Annie Franco and Gabor Simonovits, ''Science'' 345(6203):1502\u20131505 (2014)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Malhotra, Neil}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American political scientists]]\n[[Category:Yale University alumni]]\n[[Category:Stanford University alumni]]\n[[Category:Stanford University faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Pennsylvania faculty]]\n", "name_user": "Astrophobe", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eResearch:wording", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neil_Malhotra"}
