1=Sabina |title=Yearbook of Muslims in Europe |date=2014 |publisher=BRILL |page=437 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=a-NTBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA437 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Pulaha |first1=Selami |title=Defter i Sanxhakut t\u00eb Shkodr\u00ebs 1485 [Defter of the Sanjak of Shkodra in 1485 |date=1974 |publisher=Academy of Sciences of Albania |page=99 |url=https://docs.google.com/file/d/0B3ma9plMXxAEZi1PZTVXMXV1NFE/edit |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite web |title=STUDIJA O OPRAVDANOSTI OSNIVANJA OP\u0160TINE GUSINJE |url=https://www.opstinagusinje.me/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/GUSINJE-studija.pdf |website=Opstina Gusinje |publisher=Gusinje Municipality |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|author=Zajednica osnovnog obrazovanja i vaspitanja|title=Simpozijum seoski dani Sretena Vukosavljevi\u0107a|volume=11|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7WJpAAAAMAAJ|year=1986|publisher=Op\u0161tinska zajednica obrazovanja|location=Prijepolje|ref=harv}}\n\n{{Gusinje Municipality}}\n{{MontenegroCities}}\n{{commons category|Gusinje}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gusinje}}\n[[Category:Populated places in Montenegro]]\n[[Category:Sand\u017eak]]\n[[Category:Plav, Montenegro]]\n", "name_user": "Maleschreiber", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDemographics", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gusinje"}
{"title_page": "Ian Dunlop", "text_new": "{{for|the musician with International Submarine Band|Ian Dunlop (musician)}}\n{{notability|Biographies|date=May 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Ian Dunlop\n| image         = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = 1940\n| birth_place   = \n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = United Kingdom\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = writer\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n}}\n\n'''Ian Dunlop''' (born 1940) is a Scottish writer and former art critic for the ''[[Evening Standard]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/londoners-diary/french-offer-to-help-guard-the-olympics-7946258.html |title=French offer to help guard the Olympics |work=Evening Standard |location=London |date=2012-07-16 |accessdate=2016-07-11}}</ref>  His first book, ''[[The Shock of the New]]'',  about seven historic exhibitions of modern art, was published in 1972.  It was followed by books on [[Van Gogh]], and on the life and art of [[Edgar Degas]] (1979).  He has also written books and articles on contemporary American and British art and has contributed reviews and art criticism to ''[[The Times]]'',  ''[[Studio International]]'', ''[[Apollo (magazine)|Apollo]]'', ''[[The Times Literary Supplement]]'' and ''[[The Spectator]]''.\n\nDunlop was born in [[Edinburgh]], the eldest son of Commander Frederick Hamilton Dunlop, R.N. and the grandson of Sir Thomas Charles Dunlop of Doonside (1878\u20131960), sportsman, printer and publisher of the ''Ayr Advertiser''.  He was educated at [[Eton College]] and then [[Trinity College, Dublin]], where he read Mental and Moral Science. He now lives in [[London]]. In 2016, he published ''The Urban Fox'', which is his first collection of poems.\n\nBesides writing, Dunlop has worked as an art expert for [[Sotheby's]], New York and was for a time Head of Contemporary Art. He also worked as an art dealer and was a founder member of the Artis Group.\n\n== Works ==\n'''1965'''                       ''The New Generation'': 1965 introduction and notes to an exhibition of nine British sculptors at the Whitechapel Gallery, London\n\n'''1971'''                       ''Proust and Painting Proust 1871-1922'', a Centennial Volume, edited by Peter Quennel, published by Weidenfeld & Nicolson.\n\n'''1972'''                       ''Cezanne'' Introduction to the English edition of ''The Complete Paintings of Cezanne'', published by Weidenfeld & Nicolson.\n\n''The Shock of the New'', published by Weidenfeld & Nicolson.\n\n'''1973'''                       ''Van Gogh'', published by Weidenfeld & Nicolson\n\n'''1977'''                       ''Edvard Munch'', published by Thames and Hudson\n\nContributed to a number of journals and art magazines, including: ''The Dubliner, Apollo, Studio International, Connoisseur, Books and Bookmen and The Spectator, The Times Literary Supplement, The Independent on Sunday and The Times.''\n\n'''1979'''                       ''Degas'', published by Harper & Row and Phaidon\n\n'''1987'''                       ''Donald Sultan'' with Lynne Warren, catalogue introduction to an exhibition organised by the Museum of Contemporary Art, Chicago and\n\nPublished by Harry N Abrams.\n\n'''1999'''                       ''Golf'', by Bernard Darwin. Foreword by Ian Dunlop, reprinted of original 1954 edition by Ailsa Inc.\n\n'''2001'''                       ''Oxford Companion to Western Art'', ed. Brigstocke, entry on Exhibitions. Published by Oxford University Press.\n\n'''2016'''                       ''The Urban Fox'', published by Paekariki Press, Walthamstow, 2016.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikiquote-inline|Ian Dunlop}}\n* http://www.spectator.co.uk/author/ian-dunlop/\n* http://www.theoldie.co.uk/article/happy-straddling-of-science-and-art\n* http://paekakarikipress.com/?content=events.php\n* http://www.worldcat.org/title/degas/oclc/907582935&referer=brief_results\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dunlop, Ian}}\n[[Category:Writers from Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Date of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:People educated at Eton College]]\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:Art writers]]\n[[Category:Scottish art critics]]\n[[Category:Scottish male poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century Scottish poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century British male writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Scottish writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Ian Dunlop\n| image         = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = 1940\n| birth_place   = \n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = United Kingdom\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = writer\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n}}\n{{for|the musician with International Submarine Band|Ian Dunlop (musician)}}\n{{notability|Biographies|date=May 2016}}\n\n'''Ian Dunlop''' (born 1940) is a Scottish writer and former art critic for the ''[[Evening Standard]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/londoners-diary/french-offer-to-help-guard-the-olympics-7946258.html |title=French offer to help guard the Olympics |work=Evening Standard |location=London |date=2012-07-16 |accessdate=2016-07-11}}</ref>  His first book, ''[[The Shock of the New]]'',  about seven historic exhibitions of modern art, was published in 1972.  It was followed by books on [[Van Gogh]], and on the life and art of [[Edgar Degas]] (1979).  He has also written books and articles on contemporary American and British art and has contributed reviews and art criticism to ''[[The Times]]'',  ''[[Studio International]]'', ''[[Apollo (magazine)|Apollo]]'', ''[[The Times Literary Supplement]]'' and ''[[The Spectator]]''.\n\nDunlop was born in [[Edinburgh]], the eldest son of Commander Frederick Hamilton Dunlop, R.N. and the grandson of Sir Thomas Charles Dunlop of Doonside (1878\u20131960), sportsman, printer and publisher of the ''Ayr Advertiser''.  He was educated at [[Eton College]] and then [[Trinity College, Dublin]], where he read Mental and Moral Science. He now lives in [[London]]. In 2016, he published ''The Urban Fox'', which is his first collection of poems.\n\nBesides writing, Dunlop has worked as an art expert for [[Sotheby's]], New York and was for a time Head of Contemporary Art. He also worked as an art dealer and was a founder member of the Artis Group. \n\n== Works ==\n'''1965'''                       ''The New Generation'': 1965 introduction and notes to an exhibition of nine British sculptors at the Whitechapel Gallery, London\n\n'''1971'''                       ''Proust and Painting Proust 1871-1922'', a Centennial Volume, edited by Peter Quennel, published by Weidenfeld & Nicolson.\n\n'''1972'''                       ''Cezanne'' Introduction to the English edition of ''The Complete Paintings of Cezanne'', published by Weidenfeld & Nicolson.\n\n''The Shock of the New'', published by Weidenfeld & Nicolson.\n\n'''1973'''                       ''Van Gogh'', published by Weidenfeld & Nicolson\n\n'''1977'''                       ''Edvard Munch'', published by Thames and Hudson\n\nContributed to a number of journals and art magazines, including: ''The Dubliner, Apollo, Studio International, Connoisseur, Books and Bookmen and The Spectator, The Times Literary Supplement, The Independent on Sunday and The Times.''\n\n'''1979'''                       ''Degas'', published by Harper & Row and Phaidon\n\n'''1987'''                       ''Donald Sultan'' with Lynne Warren, catalogue introduction to an exhibition organised by the Museum of Contemporary Art, Chicago and\n\nPublished by Harry N Abrams.\n\n'''1999'''                       ''Golf'', by Bernard Darwin. Foreword by Ian Dunlop, reprinted of original 1954 edition by Ailsa Inc.\n\n'''2001'''                       ''Oxford Companion to Western Art'', ed. Brigstocke, entry on Exhibitions. Published by Oxford University Press.\n\n'''2016'''                       ''The Urban Fox'', published by Paekariki Press, Walthamstow, 2016.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikiquote-inline|Ian Dunlop}}\n* http://www.spectator.co.uk/author/ian-dunlop/\n* http://www.theoldie.co.uk/article/happy-straddling-of-science-and-art\n* http://paekakarikipress.com/?content=events.php\n* http://www.worldcat.org/title/degas/oclc/907582935&referer=brief_results\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dunlop, Ian}}\n[[Category:Writers from Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Date of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:People educated at Eton College]]\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:Art writers]]\n[[Category:Scottish art critics]]\n[[Category:Scottish male poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century Scottish poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century British male writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Scottish writers]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ian_Dunlop"}
{"title_page": "NASCAR Racing 2002 Season", "text_new": "{{distinguish|NASCAR Thunder 2002}}\n{{Infobox video game\n|title = NASCAR Racing 2002 Season\n|image = NASCAR Racing 2002.jpg\n|caption = Cover art featuring the cars of [[Kevin Harvick]], [[Terry Labonte]], [[Dale Jarrett]], [[Ward Burton]], and [[Jeff Burton]]\n|developer = [[Papyrus Design Group]]\n|publisher = [[Sierra Entertainment]]\n|designer =\n|released = {{Vgrelease|NA|February 14, 2002|EU|March 15, 2002}}\n|genre = [[Sim racing]]\n|modes = [[Singleplayer]], [[Multiplayer video game|Multiplayer]]\n|platforms = [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]], [[Macintosh|Mac]]\n}}\n\n'''''NASCAR Racing 2002 Season''''' is the successor to ''[[NASCAR Racing 4]]'', released in 2002.\n\n==Reception==\n{{Video game reviews\n| align = left\n| MC = 89/100<ref name=mc>{{cite web | url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/nascar-racing-2002-season | title=NASCAR Racing 2002 Season for PC Reviews | website=[[Metacritic]] | publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] | accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n| CGW = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite magazine | url=http://www.cgwmuseum.org/galleries/issues/cgw_215.pdf | title=NASCAR Racing 2002 Season | last=Hermes | first=Wade | magazine=[[Computer Gaming World]] | publisher=[[Ziff Davis]] | issue=215 | date=June 2002 | page=82 | accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n| GSpot = 8.8/10<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/nascar-racing-2002-season-review/1900-2848234/ | title=NASCAR Racing 2002 Season Review [date mislabeled as \"May 17, 2006\"] | last=Goble | first=Gord | date=February 15, 2002 | website=[[GameSpot]] | publisher=CBS Interactive | accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n| GSpy = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref>{{cite web | url=http://pc.gamespy.com/pc/nascar-racing-2002-season/543772p1.html | title=GameSpy: NASCAR Racing 2002 Season | last=Cauthen | first=John | date=April 4, 2002 | website=[[GameSpy]] | publisher=IGN Entertainment | accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n| IGN = 8.9/10<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2002/03/07/nascar-racing-2002-season-review | title=NASCAR Racing 2002 Season Review | last=Sulic | first=Ivan | date=March 7, 2002 | website=[[IGN]] | publisher=Ziff Davis | accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n| PCGUS = 93%<ref>{{cite magazine | url=http://www.pcgamer.com/archives/2005/07/nascar_racing_2_1.html | title=NASCAR Racing 2002 [Season] | last=Mahood | first=Andy | magazine=[[PC Gamer]] | publisher=[[Future US|Imagine Media]] | volume=9 | issue=5 | date=May 2002 | page=76 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060315141337/http://www.pcgamer.com/archives/2005/07/nascar_racing_2_1.html | archivedate=March 15, 2006 | url-status=dead | accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe game received \"generally favorable reviews\", just one point shy of \"universal acclaim\", according to the [[Review aggregator|review aggregation]] website [[Metacritic]].<ref name=mc/>\n\nAccording to ''[[Edge (magazine)|Edge]]'', the game sold at least 100,000 copies in the United States, but was beaten by ''NASCAR Racing 4''{{'}}s 260,000 sales in the region.<ref name=edgepcsales1>{{cite web | url=http://www.edge-online.com/features/top-100-pc-games-21st-century/3/ | title=The Top 100 PC Games of the 21st Century (Page 3) | author=Edge staff | date=August 25, 2006 | website=Edge | publisher=Future plc | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121019052748/http://www.edge-online.com/features/top-100-pc-games-21st-century/3/ | archivedate=October 19, 2012 | url-status=dead | accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref> Total US sales of ''NASCAR Racing'' computer games released in the 2000s reached 900,000 copies by August 2006.<ref name=edgepcsales1/>\n\nThe game won the award for \"2002 Best Racing Game\" at the 9th Annual ''[[PC Gamer]]'' Awards.<ref>{{cite magazine | title=The Ninth Annual PC Gamer Awards | author=PC Gamer staff | magazine=PC Gamer | publisher=Imagine Media | volume=10 | issue=3 | date=March 2003 | pages=48\u201350, 54, 58, 60, 66, 68, 70}}</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{notelist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{moby game|id=/nascar-racing-2002-season}}\n\n{{Papyrus Design Group games}}\n{{NASCAR video games}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nascar Racing 2002 Season}}\n[[Category:2002 video games]]\n[[Category:MacOS games]]\n[[Category:NASCAR video games]]\n[[Category:Papyrus Design Group games]]\n[[Category:Racing simulators]]\n[[Category:Racing video games]]\n[[Category:Sierra Entertainment games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United States]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n\n\n{{stock-racing-videogame-stub}}\n{{NASCAR-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|NASCAR Thunder 2002}}\n{{Infobox video game\n|title = NASCAR Racing 2002 Season\n|image = NASCAR Racing 2002.jpg\n|caption = Cover art featuring the cars of [[Kevin Harvick]], [[Terry Labonte]], [[Dale Jarrett]], [[Ward Burton]], and [[Jeff Burton]]\n|developer = [[Papyrus Design Group]]\n|publisher = [[Sierra Entertainment]]\n|designer =\n|released = {{Vgrelease|NA|February 14, 2002|EU|March 15, 2002}}\n|genre = [[Sim racing]]\n|modes = [[Singleplayer]], [[Multiplayer video game|Multiplayer]]\n|platforms = [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]], [[Macintosh|Mac]]\n}}\n\n'''''NASCAR Racing 2002 Season''''' is the successor to ''[[NASCAR Racing 4]]'', released in 2002.\n\n==Reception==\n{{Video game reviews\n| align = left\n| MC = 89/100<ref name=mc>{{cite web | url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/nascar-racing-2002-season | title=NASCAR Racing 2002 Season for PC Reviews | website=[[Metacritic]] | publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] | accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n| CGW = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite magazine | url=http://www.cgwmuseum.org/galleries/issues/cgw_215.pdf | title=NASCAR Racing 2002 Season | last=Hermes | first=Wade | magazine=[[Computer Gaming World]] | publisher=[[Ziff Davis]] | issue=215 | date=June 2002 | page=82 | accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n| GSpot = 8.8/10<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.gamespot.com/review